abstract: The Google Cultural Institute plans to make artifacts from around the world accessible to any Internet user.
snippet: The Google Cultural Institute plans to make artifacts from around the world accessible to any Internet user.
lead_paragraph: PARIS — When the Israel Museum in Jerusalem, home to the Dead Sea Scrolls, reopened last year after an extensive renovation, it attracted a million visitors in the first 12 months. When the museum opened an enhanced Web site with newly digitized versions of the scrolls in September, it drew a million virtual visitors in three and a half days.

headline.print_headline: Google Digitization Project Makes Artifacts Accessible to Internet Users at No Cost
